    try
    {
        parser.parse(options, args);
        fail("UnrecognizedOptionException wasn't thrown");
    }
    catch (UnrecognizedOptionException e)
    {
        assertEquals("-z", e.getOption());
    }
}
```

The test expects that when it encounters `-z` (which is not a valid option), it should throw an `UnrecognizedOptionException` with the option being `-z`. However, looking at the `burstToken` method in the `PosixParser.java` file, when an unrecognized option character is found and `stopAtNonOption` is false, it adds the whole token instead of handling it properly.

Looking at the `burstToken` method, specifically the `else` clause at the end:

```java
else
{
    tokens.add(token);  // This adds the entire token "-z" instead of handling it as an unrecognized option
    break;
}
```

